<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="10.[85,1291,850,1784]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[87,436,1515,1548]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Vieira’s Titi was discovered in 2012, and its conservation status has yet to be evaluated. While it apparently occurs over a relatively wide area,its occurrence in this area is unclear, but it may be comparable to the closely related Red-bellied Titi (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hoffmannsegg" box="[325,451,1637,1666]" class="Mammalia" family="Pitheciidae" genus="Callicebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="moloch">C. moloch</taxonomicName>
) that has a patchy distribution in the same region. Ongoing colonization projects, logging, and the construction of hydroelectric reservoirs may be a threat throughout its distribution.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
